Description: 
After a decade of Western military involvement in 
Afghanistan, reporter John Ware charts the history of the 
conflict which has so far cost more than 370 British lives 
and questions whether we will ever be able to completely 
withdraw forces from the country. Key decision makers, 
including Prime Minister David Cameron and former 
president of Pakistan Pervez Musharraf, also discuss how 
the original strategy of getting in and out in a matter of 
months and employing a small number of ground troops 
has turned into ten years of grinding conflict with more 
than 140,000 personnel deployed.
